[28:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'called Polaris and this is a new method for improving the reasoning of language models using reinforcement learning. And you can add this to any existing model that\'s finished training. So for'

[29:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example, you can add it to Quen or Llama or DeepSeek and just from this post-training technique, it can make the model even better. Here\'s the craziest breakthrough. For example, they applied this Polaris fine-tuning on Quen 34B.'

[29:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is a really tiny model of only 4 billion parameters. Here\'s the original performance of Quen 34B. But after going through this Polaris fine-tuning or post-training method, note the huge jump'

[29:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in performance for this AIM benchmark. Notice that this even beats Gro 3 and Claude 4 Opus, which is the best and biggest variant of Claude 4. Plus, it even beats 03 Mini High and Gemini 2.5'

[29:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Flash. Note that the crazy thing is this is only 4 billion parameters. I would suspect that Gro 3 or Claude 4 would be like at least hundreds of billions of parameters. Note that the original'

[29:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Deepseek R1 is 671 billion parameters. So this fine-tune using Polaris is able to outperform models that are over 160 times its size. So this is quite technical, but I\'ll try to explain this'

[30:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in simple terms. In a nutshell, here\'s how Polaris works. First of all, before training, Polaris makes sure the training data is neither too easy nor too hard for the model. It does this by'

[30:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'filtering out problems that are too easy and only keeping a mix of problems that challenge the model just enough. As the model gets better, it also removes problems that have become too easy so'

[30:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that the model is always learning from challenging examples. And then it also uses diverse examples when it\'s training the model and it varies how the model generates the answers by adjusting what is called the sampling temperature. And'

[30:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this encourages the model to explore different ways of reasoning and not just repeat what it already knows. And then over here basically Polaris also gradually increases the length and complexity of the training examples and'

[31:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this allows the model to handle longer more complex reasoning without overwhelming it at the start. So basically the questions get harder and it needs to think for longer as it proceeds with the training. So in short,'

[31:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Polaris is a way to train an existing model further by using reinforcement learning. And this can improve its performance by a lot. It can even take a tiny 4 billion parameter model and'

[31:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'improve its performance to be on par with other leading models that are hundreds of parameters in size. The nice thing is they\'ve opensourced everything including the data set, the training details and the code. So if you click on'

