VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this main page in the description below. In other news, Nvidia released this super powerful tool called Align Your Flow. Now, this is quite technical, but I\'ll try to explain this'

[32:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in simple terms. Now, usually in image generation, whether you\'re using Hydream or Flux or Stable Diffusion, when you generate the image, you need to set the number of steps for the image. Now, usually image generators require like 10'

[32:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to 30 steps to generate a good quality image. But of course, this takes a lot more time and compute to generate. So you can see from this chart here, the blue line is diffusion models like stable diffusion, flux and hindam which'

[32:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are like the top models out there and the y-axis is the FID which is a metric of quality. So the lower this value the better the quality. As you can see for diffusion models it requires like 30 to 40 steps before you actually get good'

[32:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'quality images. But this takes so much time. Wouldn\'t it be nice if you can just generate nice images in just one or two steps? So that\'s exactly what align your flow does. So here\'s what they did. They first took a data set called'

[32:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'imageet 512 x 512 which contains over a million images that are similar to this. They then trained this align your flow model with these images to create a flow map model. This is essentially an image'

[33:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generator. Now when you prompt this image generator to generate some photos in just one step it was able to generate all these photos. I mean this is pretty good considering it\'s only doing this for one step. Whereas for flux or stable'

[33:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'diffusion, you often need like 20 to 30 steps just to see a good quality result. Now, instead of one step, here are some images with two steps as you can see here. Now, instead of using imageet as'

[33:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the training data set, you can also use an image generator like SDXL or Flux to use as the teacher. In other words, you first get these existing AI models to generate images which can then be used'

[33:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to train this align your flow model. And that\'s exactly what they did. So they used Fluxdev to generate images to train their flow map model and here are some results. So on the right column is'

[33:56] [scene:talk]
